6. Implementation

6.1 Programming Language

Python was chosen because:


It is easy to understand

Supports structured programming

Ideal for beginners
6.2 Sample Code Snippet
tasks = []
def add_task():

title = input("Enter task title: ")
priority = input("Enter priority (High/Medium/Low): ")

tasks.append({"title": title, "priority": priority, "status": "Pending"})


print("Task added successfully!")

def view_tasks():

for t in tasks:

print(f"{t['title']} - {t['priority']} - {t['status']}")

add_task()

view_tasks()




7. Results and Discussion


The application successfully performs the following:

Adds tasks with priority levels

Displays tasks in a clean format

Allows updating and deleting of tasks

Marks tasks as completed

This classification based on priorities allows the user to focus on urgent tasks first.

The project demonstrates the handling of data, conditional logic, and modular programming.



-

8. Advantages

Simple and easy to use

Helps in organizing daily activities

Improves time management



Priority levels determine the importance of a task.

Easily extensible to either GUI or mobile app development



9. Limitations

Currently text-based-no GUI

No automatic reminders

Limited storage (unless JSON or database is used)



10. Future Enhancements

Add deadlines and notifications

Create Graphical User Interface: Tkinter/HTML Adding categories for tasks Leverage databases for big data storage. Introduce a login system for multiple users --- 

11. Conclusion The To-Do List with Priority Levels project represents a very useful application that is practical, and which assists users in managing their tasks effectively.
It demonstrates core programming concepts such as data structures, file handling, functions, and user input handling. The project is simple but effective and serves as a robust foundation for higher-level task management systems.
